snippet.textDisplay: The 150 MPH/240 km/h sticker in Germany has to be put into any car if there are tyres fit that do not exceed the exact. max speed of the vehicle. This also applies for those limited at 250 km/h with tyres up to 240 km/h although there is a pretty wide safety margin. During the winter months this is actually very common with winter tyres. The car just has the wrong tyres. Of course those cars come from factory with tyres rated for 270 (W) or 300 km/h (Y).

There is a reason this Panamera is a "steal" at $30,000.....
It's 8 years old

No Warranty
V6 not V8
Ask how much an oil change costs (you want to use non-Porsche, cheapo brand?? Good luck!)
Ask how much does Anti-freeze / power-steering fluids, heck, ANY Porsche-only fluid cost to replace!
Ask how much their "Scheduled Maintenance" costs (yeah, that will give you a butt hurt!)
Ask how much it costs to replace the tires
Ask how much insurance costs.....
Google or ask any bodyshop how much it costs to fix any XYZ item (from headlights to a minor dent....)
And the transmission..how much will that cost to replace???
Do you know how much it costs to fix ANY electrical problem in a used German car?? Go ahead, ask a mechanic or google it!!

Etc etc etc
